#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:17
msgid ""
"The series in this context are finite sums of the corresponding polynomial "
"basis functions multiplied by coefficients. For instance, a power series "
"looks like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:21
msgid ""
"p(x) = 1 + 2x + 3x^2\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:23
msgid ""
"and has coefficients :math:`[1, 2, 3]`. The Chebyshev series with the same "
"coefficients looks like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:27
msgid ""
"p(x) = 1 T_0(x) + 2 T_1(x) + 3 T_2(x)\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:29
msgid "and more generally"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:31
msgid ""
"p(x) = \\sum_{i=0}^n c_i T_i(x)\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:33
msgid ""
"where in this case the :math:`T_n` are the Chebyshev functions of degree :"
"math:`n`, but could just as easily be the basis functions of any of the "
"other classes. The convention for all the classes is that the coefficient :"
"math:`c[i]` goes with the basis function of degree i."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:38
msgid ""
"All of the classes are immutable and have the same methods, and especially "
"they implement the Python numeric operators +, -, \\*, //, %, divmod, "
"\\*\\*, ==, and !=. The last two can be a bit problematic due to floating "
"point roundoff errors. We now give a quick demonstration of the various "
"operations using NumPy version 1.7.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:45
msgid "Basics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:47
msgid ""
"First we need a polynomial class and a polynomial instance to play with. The "
"classes can be imported directly from the polynomial package or from the "
"module of the relevant type. Here we import from the package and use the "
"conventional Polynomial class because of its familiarity::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:52
msgid ""
">>> from numpy.polynomial import Polynomial as P\n"
">>> p = P([1,2,3])\n"
">>> p\n"
"Polynomial([1., 2., 3.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:57
msgid ""
"Note that there are three parts to the long version of the printout. The "
"first is the coefficients, the second is the domain, and the third is the "
"window::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:61
msgid ""
">>> p.coef\n"
"array([1., 2., 3.])\n"
">>> p.domain\n"
"array([-1.,  1.])\n"
">>> p.window\n"
"array([-1.,  1.])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:68
msgid ""
"Printing a polynomial yields the polynomial expression in a more familiar "
"format::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:71
msgid ""
">>> print(p)\n"
"1.0 + 2.0·x + 3.0·x²"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:74
msgid ""
"Note that the string representation of polynomials uses Unicode characters "
"by default (except on Windows) to express powers and subscripts. An ASCII-"
"based representation is also available (default on Windows). The polynomial "
"string format can be toggled at the package-level with the `~numpy."
"polynomial.set_default_printstyle` function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:80
msgid ""
">>> np.polynomial.set_default_printstyle('ascii')\n"
">>> print(p)\n"
"1.0 + 2.0 x + 3.0 x**2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:84
msgid ""
"or controlled for individual polynomial instances with string formatting::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:86
msgid ""
">>> print(f\"{p:unicode}\")\n"
"1.0 + 2.0·x + 3.0·x²"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:89
msgid ""
"We will deal with the domain and window when we get to fitting, for the "
"moment we ignore them and run through the basic algebraic and arithmetic "
"operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:92
msgid "Addition and Subtraction::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:94
msgid ""
">>> p + p\n"
"Polynomial([2., 4., 6.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')\n"
">>> p - p\n"
"Polynomial([0.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:99
msgid "Multiplication::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:101
msgid ""
">>> p * p\n"
"Polynomial([ 1.,   4.,  10.,  12.,   9.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  "
"1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:104
msgid "Powers::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:106
msgid ""
">>> p**2\n"
"Polynomial([ 1.,   4., 10., 12.,  9.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], "
"symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:109
msgid "Division:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:111
msgid ""
"Floor division, '//', is the division operator for the polynomial classes, "
"polynomials are treated like integers in this regard. For Python versions < "
"3.x the '/' operator maps to '//', as it does for Python, for later versions "
"the '/' will only work for division by scalars. At some point it will be "
"deprecated::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:117
msgid ""
">>> p // P([-1, 1])\n"
"Polynomial([5.,  3.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:120
msgid "Remainder::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:122
msgid ""
">>> p % P([-1, 1])\n"
"Polynomial([6.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:125
msgid "Divmod::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:127
msgid ""
">>> quo, rem = divmod(p, P([-1, 1]))\n"
">>> quo\n"
"Polynomial([5.,  3.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')\n"
">>> rem\n"
"Polynomial([6.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:133
msgid "Evaluation::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:135
msgid ""
">>> x = np.arange(5)\n"
">>> p(x)\n"
"array([  1.,   6.,  17.,  34.,  57.])\n"
">>> x = np.arange(6).reshape(3,2)\n"
">>> p(x)\n"
"array([[ 1.,   6.],\n"
"       [17.,  34.],\n"
"       [57.,  86.]])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:144
msgid "Substitution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:146
msgid ""
"Substitute a polynomial for x and expand the result. Here we substitute p in "
"itself leading to a new polynomial of degree 4 after expansion. If the "
"polynomials are regarded as functions this is composition of functions::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:151
msgid ""
">>> p(p)\n"
"Polynomial([ 6., 16., 36., 36., 27.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], "
"symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:154
msgid "Roots::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:156
msgid ""
">>> p.roots()\n"
"array([-0.33333333-0.47140452j, -0.33333333+0.47140452j])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:161
msgid ""
"It isn't always convenient to explicitly use Polynomial instances, so "
"tuples, lists, arrays, and scalars are automatically cast in the arithmetic "
"operations::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:165
msgid ""
">>> p + [1, 2, 3]\n"
"Polynomial([2., 4., 6.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')\n"
">>> [1, 2, 3] * p\n"
"Polynomial([ 1.,  4., 10., 12.,  9.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], "
"symbol='x')\n"
">>> p / 2\n"
"Polynomial([0.5, 1. , 1.5], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:172
msgid ""
"Polynomials that differ in domain, window, or class can't be mixed in "
"arithmetic::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:175
msgid ""
">>> from numpy.polynomial import Chebyshev as T\n"
">>> p + P([1], domain=[0,1])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n"
"  File \"<string>\", line 213, in __add__\n"
"TypeError: Domains differ\n"
">>> p + P([1], window=[0,1])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n"
"  File \"<string>\", line 215, in __add__\n"
"TypeError: Windows differ\n"
">>> p + T([1])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n"
"  File \"<string>\", line 211, in __add__\n"
"TypeError: Polynomial types differ"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:193
msgid ""
"But different types can be used for substitution. In fact, this is how "
"conversion of Polynomial classes among themselves is done for type, domain, "
"and window casting::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:197
msgid ""
">>> p(T([0, 1]))\n"
"Chebyshev([2.5, 2. , 1.5], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:200
msgid ""
"Which gives the polynomial `p` in Chebyshev form. This works because :math:"
"`T_1(x) = x` and substituting :math:`x` for :math:`x` doesn't change the "
"original polynomial. However, all the multiplications and divisions will be "
"done using Chebyshev series, hence the type of the result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:205
msgid ""
"It is intended that all polynomial instances are immutable, therefore "
"augmented operations (``+=``, ``-=``, etc.) and any other functionality that "
"would violate the immutablity of a polynomial instance are intentionally "
"unimplemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:211
msgid "Calculus"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:213
msgid "Polynomial instances can be integrated and differentiated.::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:215
msgid ""
">>> from numpy.polynomial import Polynomial as P\n"
">>> p = P([2, 6])\n"
">>> p.integ()\n"
"Polynomial([0., 2., 3.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')\n"
">>> p.integ(2)\n"
"Polynomial([0., 0., 1., 1.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], "
"symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:222
msgid ""
"The first example integrates `p` once, the second example integrates it "
"twice. By default, the lower bound of the integration and the integration "
"constant are 0, but both can be specified.::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:226
msgid ""
">>> p.integ(lbnd=-1)\n"
"Polynomial([-1.,  2.,  3.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], "
"symbol='x')\n"
">>> p.integ(lbnd=-1, k=1)\n"
"Polynomial([0., 2., 3.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:231
msgid ""
"In the first case the lower bound of the integration is set to -1 and the "
"integration constant is 0. In the second the constant of integration is set "
"to 1 as well. Differentiation is simpler since the only option is the number "
"of times the polynomial is differentiated::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:236
msgid ""
">>> p = P([1, 2, 3])\n"
">>> p.deriv(1)\n"
"Polynomial([2., 6.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')\n"
">>> p.deriv(2)\n"
"Polynomial([6.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:244
msgid "Other polynomial constructors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:246
msgid ""
"Constructing polynomials by specifying coefficients is just one way of "
"obtaining a polynomial instance, they may also be created by specifying "
"their roots, by conversion from other polynomial types, and by least squares "
"fits. Fitting is discussed in its own section, the other methods are "
"demonstrated below::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:252
msgid ""
">>> from numpy.polynomial import Polynomial as P\n"
">>> from numpy.polynomial import Chebyshev as T\n"
">>> p = P.fromroots([1, 2, 3])\n"
">>> p\n"
"Polynomial([-6., 11., -6.,  1.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], "
"symbol='x')\n"
">>> p.convert(kind=T)\n"
"Chebyshev([-9.  , 11.75, -3.  ,  0.25], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  "
"1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:260
msgid "The convert method can also convert domain and window::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:262
msgid ""
">>> p.convert(kind=T, domain=[0, 1])\n"
"Chebyshev([-2.4375 ,  2.96875, -0.5625 ,  0.03125], domain=[0.,  1.], "
"window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')\n"
">>> p.convert(kind=P, domain=[0, 1])\n"
"Polynomial([-1.875,  2.875, -1.125,  0.125], domain=[0.,  1.], window=[-1.,  "
"1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:267
msgid ""
"In numpy versions >= 1.7.0 the `basis` and `cast` class methods are also "
"available. The cast method works like the convert method while the basis "
"method returns the basis polynomial of given degree::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:271
msgid ""
">>> P.basis(3)\n"
"Polynomial([0., 0., 0., 1.], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], "
"symbol='x')\n"
">>> T.cast(p)\n"
"Chebyshev([-9.  , 11.75, -3. ,  0.25], domain=[-1.,  1.], window=[-1.,  1.], "
"symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:276
msgid ""
"Conversions between types can be useful, but it is *not* recommended for "
"routine use. The loss of numerical precision in passing from a Chebyshev "
"series of degree 50 to a Polynomial series of the same degree can make the "
"results of numerical evaluation essentially random."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:282
msgid "Fitting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:284
msgid ""
"Fitting is the reason that the `domain` and `window` attributes are part of "
"the convenience classes. To illustrate the problem, the values of the "
"Chebyshev polynomials up to degree 5 are plotted below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:299
msgid ""
"In the range -1 <= `x` <= 1 they are nice, equiripple functions lying "
"between +/- 1. The same plots over the range -2 <= `x` <= 2 look very "
"different:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.classes.rst:313
msgid ""
"As can be seen, the \"good\" parts have shrunk to insignificance. In using "
"Chebyshev polynomials for fitting we want to use the region where `x` is "
"between -1 and 1 and that is what the `window` specifies. However, it is "
"unlikely that the data to be fit has all its data points in that interval, "
"so we use `domain` to specify the interval where the data points lie. When "
"the fit is done, the domain is first mapped to the window by a linear "
"transformation and the usual least squares fit is done using the mapped data "
"points. The window and domain of the fit are part of the returned series and "
"are automatically used when computing values, derivatives, and such. If they "
"aren't specified in the call the fitting routine will use the default window "
"and the smallest domain that holds all the data points. This is illustrated "
"below for a fit to a noisy sine curve."
msgstr ""
